<http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/2003/01/11/stories/2003011103900300.htm>

India (Kerala): Dengue-related Deaths in City of Thiruvananthapuram
--------------------------------------------------
There have been 18 confirmed cases of dengue fever so far in the district.
Addressing a press conference, the District Medical Officer, (DMO) K.
Shailaja, said that a total of 80 serum samples had been subjected to
microbiological examination. The DMO sought community participation in
vector control measures targeted at reducing the density of the mosquito
species -- _Aedes egypti_ and _Aedes albopictus_ -- which transmit dengue
virus to humans. Dr. Shailaja underlined the importance of coordinated
efforts among various departments and the public for achieving effective
vector control. Maintaining environmental hygiene was an important
component of vector control measures. There have been 2 dengue-related
deaths in the city so far. Melaranoor and Vizhinjam, where the deaths
occurred, have been declared dengue-prone areas.
According to the DMO, initial dengue infection is self- limiting and
harmless. However, a repeat infection could potentially lead to serious
medical conditions like dengue hemorraghic fever and dengue shock syndrome.
The mortality rate of dengue fever was between 1.5 percent and 23 percent
if the treatment involved a major hospital. The typical features of the
disease ranged from high fever, pain in the posterior of the eye, headache,
and body pain, and management hinged on symptomatic treatment. The vector
species breed in domestic as well as external habitats. Outlining the
measures taken by the health department, Dr. Shailaja said fogging and
pesticidal measures were concentrated at dengue outbreak sites. Rapid
action forces had been formed at the district, block, and grama panchayat
levels to check the spread of fever.
--
