Source: Daily News (Sri Lanka), Fri 17 Jan 2003 [edited]

Sri Lanka: 67 Suspected Dengue Fever Cases Reported
-------------------------------------------------
The dengue epidemic has claimed at least 4 lives so far during this year,
health officials warned yesterday. The warning came amidst reports of one
death and a large number of suspected cases from the Puttalam district last
week. "We have got 3 unreported deaths from the same district so far," a
senior epidemiologist told the Daily News yesterday.
So far 67 suspected cases have been reported with the highest originating
from the Puttalam District with the Matara district ranking second. The
epidemiologist attributed the outbreak to the change in the weather pattern
and the carelessness of the people to keep the environment around them
clean. However, he said steps have been taken to bring the situation under
control in collaboration with the local government authorities.
During the last year, the highest number of dengue cases was reported from
the Western Province, especially from Colombo, Gampaha, and Maharagama.
Health authorities launched a special program to counter the dengue
epidemic in high risk areas such as Maharagama, Dehiwala, and Moratuwa, and
houses in those areas will be inspected every week.
[Byline: Bharatha Malawaraarachchi]
--
