Malaysia: Dengue Fever Outbreak in Perak State
----------------------------------------------
The Ipoh City Council and the Kinta Health Department will join forces "to
clean up" the cluster of villages in the Manjoi area to rid it of _Aedes_
mosquitoes and allay the fear of some 24 400 residents in the locality.
This is in view of the death of 3 children in Manjoi over the last 2 weeks
after they were believed to have contracted dengue fever. State Health,
Science, Technology and Environment Committee chairman Datuk Ho Cheng Wang
said the authorities were working hard to clean up drains, clear up
containers, and carry out inspection of homes.
Manjoi which comprises Kampung Tengku Hussein, Kampung Sungai Tapah, and
Kampung Datuk Ahmad Said, comes under the purview of the council as the
people have been paying assessment to the local authority over the past few
years, but control of vector-borne diseases is still the responsibility of
the Kinta health department. Ho said the council had yet to take over the
responsibility, as it was short of staff.
2 days ago, a year-4 pupil of Sekolah Kebangsaan Manjoi died of dengue
haemorrhagic fever. The 10-year-old boy died of at 7 a.m., 8 days after he
was admitted to the Ipoh Hospital. Earlier, 2 children, a girl and a boy,
both 2 years old from the area, died of dengue on 3 and 7 Jan 2003,
respectively.
He said there were 1805 dengue-positive cases in the State last year,
compared to 983 the previous year. "There were 12 deaths last year compared
to 7 in 2001. Most of the dengue cases were reported in urban localities of
Taiping, Kuala Kangsar, and Ipoh," he said.
[Byline: V. Anbalagan]
