Taiwan: Imported Dengue Fever Case Confirmed in Taichung
--------------------------------------------------
Health officials in Taichung County are warning anyone with symptoms of
dengue fever to seek medical attention, after a man in the area was found
to have brought the disease back with him from Thailand.
Officials at the Department of Health's Center for Disease Control said
they had confirmed the first case of dengue fever in Taichung County on 10
Jan 2003. The man, who works as a sales representative for a manufacturing
company, is thought to have contracted the disease while on a business trip
to Thailand last year [2002]. He traveled to Thailand in December 2002 and
returned to Taiwan on 21 Dec 2002, health officials said.
The man was reported as living in Taichung County's Shenkang Township and
working in the nearby Waipu Township. People in both areas are being warned
that they should be on the lookout for symptoms common to dengue fever. On
26 Dec 2002, the man started to run a fever and checked into Taichung
City's Chung Shan Medical University Hospital on the 30 Dec 2002. Hospital
officials informed the Center for Disease Control (CDC) of the case and
forwarded samples taken from the man for testing. CDC officials confirmed
that the man was suffering from dengue fever on the same day. An inspection
team was sent to the man's house and place of work the next day to spray
for mosquitoes and check up on the man's family. Environmental officials
were asked to clean up the area around where the man lived and worked to
make sure that mosquitoes carrying the disease would not be able to
reproduce. Tests conducted on 32 people who came into contact with the man
all came up negative, leading health officials to express guarded
[optimism] that an outbreak of dengue fever was not imminent.
An outbreak of endemic dengue fever has been ravaging southern Taiwan since
summer 2002 and could continue into next summer.
